name: Site/area management
note: Restoration management strategy requires reduction of the external and internal organic load, control of non-point pollution sources, control of hydrological regime, and establishment of bio-manipulation techniques.

name: Habitat & natural process restoration
note: The reintroduction of traditional farming activities in order to maintain a high diversity in the Mediterranean landscape

name: Resource & habitat protection
note: Protect remaining areas of laurel forest.

name: Captive breeding/artificial propagation
note: Ex-situ breeding followed by a species reintroduction program.

name: Habitat & natural process restoration
note: Continue to promote the restoration of dry and laurel forests.

name: Invasive/problematic species control
note: Control introduced predators at breeding sites, particularly on Tenerife.

name: Site/area management
note: Avoid further damage to laurel forest from commercial forestry.

name: Sub-national level
note: Control illegal hunting, especially at drinking sites.

name: Awareness & communications
note: Continue ongoing education and awareness campaigns.

name: Site/area protection
note: Ensure the adequate protection of key sites, particularly as yet unprotected ones on La Gomera and La Palma.

name: Species recovery
note: Develop and implement a new national Conservation Plan (J. A. Lorenzo in litt. 2016).

name: Site/area management
note: *Prevent further habitat loss through livestock grazing.

name: Awareness & communications
note: *Undertake an education campaign to overcome the species's unpopularity.

name: Awareness & communications
note: *Promote the use of bird scarers to reduce agricultural damage.

name: Site/area protection
note: *Identify and protect new areas of laurel forest.

name: Resource & habitat protection
note: Develop a plan to prevent forest fires. Prevent the clearance of dead and rotting trunks in managed forests.

name: Site/area protection
note: Prevent the logging of mature Corsican pine.

name: Invasive/problematic species control
note: Continue and increase rat and cat control programmes.

name: Site/area protection
note: Control human access and disturbance to breeding sites through purchasing and wardening of the breeding area.

name: Reintroduction
note: Consider (re-)introducing the species to other islets in the Azores, reducing the potential impact of rodents being introduced to one of the current breeding islets.

name: Invasive/problematic species control
note: It is important to control Hedychium gardnerianum, as this is one of the major threats to the integrity of native vegetation in the Azores.

name: Invasive/problematic species control
note: The invasion of species such as Hedychium gardnerianum and Pittosporum undulatum would benefit the habitat of this liverwort.

name: Site/area protection
note: Continue to protect the areas where the species occur.

name: International level
note: The species is the only bryophyte (liverwort) mentioned in the TOP 100 species that should be protected in Macaronesia (Martin et al., 2008). However this document is not legally binding.

name: Sub-national level
note: The species is protected by Azorean law - DLR 15/2012 from 2 April, that includes it under its Annex II "Protected species that occur in the wild in the terrestrial and marine Azorean territory".

name: Site/area protection
note: Native forests in the Azores (habitat 45 of the Habitats Directive), are under threat because they are restricted to very small areas, surrounded by humanized landscape. Natural corridors and tampoon areas would benefit the species.

name: Formal education
note: Students of Biology and other natural sciences degrees should be aware of liverworts in general and the endemic species in particular.

name: Training
note: Since this is one of the few endemic species of liverwort, and possible to recognize in the field, all nature guides working in the Protected Areas of the Azores should be aware of its characteristics, to be able to monitor the populations inside the Natural Parks.

name: Awareness & communications
note: The general public in the Azores should be aware of its rich natural heritage. Bazzania azorica is one of the most atractive liverwort species and could be promoted as a natural icon.

name: Resource & habitat protection
note: The native forests of the Azores are probably the most diverse habitat of the Region and many endemic species are encroached there. Although the habitat is mentioned in Annex I of the European Habitats Directive (habitat 45), the threats to its prevalence should be taken seriously - area reduction, alterations due to climate change, alterations due to invasion of exotic species, and constant monitoring should be put in place.

name: Invasive/problematic species control
note: This is probably one of the most serious threats to the conservation of species restricted to native forests. Hedychium gardnerianum and Pittosporum undulatum should be carefully managed within the forest areas where Bazzania azorica occurs.

name: Site/area management
note: Within the scope of the management plans for Natura 2000 sites, proper water abstractions management is needed to avoid drastic changes in the water regime that make the water courses unsuitable for O. cazuma larval development.

name: National level
note: The species should be included in the national list of threatened species to ensure its conservation throughout the territory.

name: National level
note: *Ensure adequate protection under the Countryside Law and Wildlife Protection Law.

name: Site/area management
note:
Prevent forest fires.

Carry out further work to divert recreational activities from important sites.

name: Habitat & natural process restoration
note: Forest management should focus on thinning areas of dense pine trees (as in Garca-del-Rey et al. 2010) where no undergrowth persists and reafforesting areas within the former range of pine forests on the islands (Garca-del-Rey and Cresswell 2005). Investigation of habitat suitability recommends management of forests above 1,100 m a.s.l. with a summer precipitation of 13-14 mm, by reducing canopy cover to 25-50% and thinning (Carrascal et al., 2017).

name: Reintroduction
note: Consider translocations to currently unoccupied but suitable habitat, such as Tamadaba (which has recorded historical presence (Keller et al., 2020))

name: National level
note: Ensure adequate protection under the Countryside Law and Wildlife Protection Law.

name: Habitat & natural process restoration

name: Linked enterprises & livelihood alternatives
note: Promote land use changes in the buffer areas around the SPA.

name: Site/area management
note: Continue the removal and exclusion of exotic flora.

name: Habitat & natural process restoration
note: Continue the replanting of native vegetation (particularly key food plants).

name: Awareness & communications
note: Improved visitor information with exclusion of walkers from key locations

name: Resource & habitat protection
note: Protection of groundwater from over-abstraction or pollution.

name: Resource & habitat protection
note: Maintain woodlands in a natural state, retaining any old trees and dead wood, ensuring continuity of these habitats in the future.

name: Site/area protection
note: Identify and protect key areas of optimal habitat for the species (Illera 1999, 2001, 2004).

name: Awareness & communications
note: Raise awareness of the species among the resident and tourist populations, particularly the threat from off-road driving and introduced mammals (Illera 1999, 2004).

name: National level
note: Develop, approve and implement a national Conservation Plan for the species (Illera 2004).

name: Invasive/problematic species control
note: Attempt to control introduced predators, particularly rats Rattus spp. and feral cats Felis catus, at key sites where their impact on breeding success is particularly severe (Illera 2004). Reduce the number of "coastal goats" in areas of optimal habitat for the species (Illera 1999, 2001, 2004).
